      • addRegistry

        public Registry<V> addRegistry(@NotNull
                               @NotNull java.util.Map<RegistryIdentifier,RegistryColumn<V>> otherRegistry)
        Adds another Registry to this one. If the added Registry contains the same RegistryIdentifiers, then that data will be added to the existing columns. The difference between this method and addRegistry(Registry) is that this allows the direct insertion of a Map instance instead of requiring a pre-existing registry.
        Parameters:
        otherRegistry - The other Registry to add to this one.
        Returns:
        Itself.

      • removeColumnsIf

        public Registry<V> removeColumnsIf(java.util.function.Predicate<RegistryIdentifier> filter)
        Filter the Registry by its columns. Note this creates a new Registry and doesn't modify itself.
        Parameters:
        filter - The filter accepts a RegistryIdentifier and returns true to remove that column, false to keep it. The columns which pass the filter are stored in a new Registry.
        Returns:
        The new Registry containing the filtered columns.

      • removeColumnsIf

        public Registry<V> removeColumnsIf(java.util.function.BiPredicate<RegistryIdentifier,RegistryColumn<? super V>> biFilter)
        Filter the Registry by its columns. Note this creates a new Registry and doesn't modify itself.
        Parameters:
        biFilter - The biFilter accepts a RegistryIdentifier, along with its RegistryColumn and returns true to remove that column, false to keep it. The columns which pass the filter are stored in a new Registry.
        Returns:
        The new Registry containing the filtered columns.

      • removeValuesIf

        public Registry<V> removeValuesIf(java.util.function.Predicate<? super V> filter)
        Filter the Registry by its values. Note this creates a new Registry and doesn't modify itself.
        Parameters:
        filter - The filter accepts a value of type V or its parents and returns true to remove that column, false to keep it. The values which pass the filter are stored in a new Registry. If no values in a particular column pass the filter, it is still added to the new Registry, it will simply contain no values.
        Returns:
        The new Registry containing the filtered values.

      • removeValuesIf

        public Registry<V> removeValuesIf(java.util.function.BiPredicate<RegistryIdentifier,? super V> biFilter)
        Filter the Registry by its values. Note this creates a new Registry and doesn't modify itself.
        Parameters:
        biFilter - The biFilter accepts a RegistryIdentifier (The columnID of the value), along with a value of type V or its parents and returns true to remove that column, false to keep it. The values which pass the filter are stored in a new Registry. If no values in a particular column pass the filter, it is still added to the new Registry, it will simply contain no values.
        Returns:
        The new Registry containing the filtered values.
